VL  - 31
IS  - 9
SP  - 3687
EP  - 3688
SN  - 0893-9454
AB  - In the original publication of “The Causal Effect of Stop-Loss and Take-Gain Orders on the Disposition Effect” by Urs Fischbacher, Gerson Hoffmann, and Simeon Schudy (https://doi.org/10.1093/rfs/hhx016), that published in 30(6), there was an inconsistency in the lower part of Table 1 (page 2124). Table 1 (correctly) displayed means of individual average distances for “Limit Choices” and “Sales in the last round (forced)” but (incorrectly) reported means over all observations for “Unforced sales (sales in all but last round)”. An updated version of Table 1 which reports the means of individual average distances for “Unforced sales” and corrects for rounding errors can be found below. Differences in reported values do not affect the conclusions of the paper as all statistical tests already referred to the correct means over individual averages. We note however, that the original statement on page 2125, “For all unforced realizations, that is, for all gains and losses realized before the last round, losses and gains of investors using both limits tend to be smaller in the limit than in the no limit treatment but the differences are statistically insignificant (Wilcoxon rank-sum test, two-sided, using individual averages, for losses ${\rm p}=0.627$, for gains ${\rm p}=0.556$)” should be rephrased as “For all unforced realizations, that is, for all gains and losses realized before the last round, relative distances of the weighted purchase price to the selling price do not differ statistically significantly (Wilcoxon rank-sum test, two-sided, using individual averages, for losses ${\rm p} = 0.627$, for gains ${\rm p} = 0.556$).”
Y2  - 3/26/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/rfs/hhy056
ER  - 



